<br><b>44. Define Torsion</b>
<br>
<br>When a pair of forces of equal magnitude but opposite directions acting on body, it tends to twist the body. It is known as twisting moment or torsional moment or simply as torque.
<br>Torque is equal to the product of the force applied and the distance between the point of application of the force and the axis of the shaft. 
<br>
<br><b>45. What are the assumptions made in Torsion equation</b>
<br>
<br>• The material of the shaft is homogeneous, perfectly elastic and obeys Hooke's law.
<br>&bull; Twist is uniform along the length of the shaft
<br>&bull; The stress does not exceed the limit of proportionality
<br>&bull; The shaft circular in section remains circular after loading
<br>&bull; Strain and deformations are small. 
<br>
<br><b>46. Define polar modulus</b>
<br>
<br>It is the ratio between polar moment of inertia and radius of the shaft.
<br>£ = polar moment of inertia/Radius = J/ R 
<br>
